Influenza A viremia has been reported during acute-phase illness, mainly in patients infected with more pathogenic influenza viruses, such as H5N1 (
 
  8
 ). Our study demonstrates the asymptomatic presence of influenza A virus RNA in blood donors preceding symptom onset, which provides theoretical grounds for the possibility of influenza transmission by blood transfusion. A study performed by the American Red Cross on 1,004 samples from blood donors reporting postdonation influenza symptoms detected no influenza-positive samples by RT-PCR during the first H1N1 outbreak in 2009 in the United States (
 
  5
 ). Other studies conducted during the 2009 H1N1 pandemic also detected no viral RNA in persons who donated blood during the incubation period and in whom influenza symptoms developed 2âˆ’7 days after donation (
 
